@node WhatItIs "What the hell is it?"

   @{u}You really don't know?@{uu}

   MAX-FileGuide  is  a  MAX's BBS  support  program,  which allows you to
 generate  complete  file  list  of  your  BBS files in a nice AmigaGuide
 format.  Only  files described in your "file.data" database file will be
 listed.  No  files stored on e.g. CD-ROM and accesed by any door will be
 included in this file list.

@endnode


@node HowItWorks "I wonder how it works..."

   @{u}How it works?@{uu}

   It's so simply.... To obtain all information required to generate file
 list,  program  needs  the  following  files  to  process as input data:
 "maxbbs.config"  which  contains  section  names  and  related data, and
 "file.data"  with  whole information about each file known by MAX's BBS.
 First  of  all,  program generates list of non empty sections. Non empty
 means,  that section has its name (title) *AND* it contains at least one
 file (if you specify @{" PATTERN " link Usage} section name must match the pattern too).
 Filtered  sections  are  then  sorting  by  its name (title) to make any
 future  search-by-topic  bit  easier (if you do not like your users, and
 want to make them sweat, just disable this feature with @{" NOSECTIONSORT " link Usage} 
 :).  When  this  operation is finished, program starts to proces largest
 file  in its life: "file.data". This operation takes 90% of time used to
 create  while  AmigaGuide  document  because  of alphabetical file sort
 needed  to  be  perform.  However,  because  of  fast sort-while-reading
 routines  it  take  more less the same time to scan this database and to
 scan and sort.
  At  the  end  it  includes your messages into document, if there's any.
 Please notice, that messages are *NOT* sorted at all. Do it yourself and
 set in the right queue.

@endnode


@node WhyThisOne "Why ahouls I use this one?"

   @{u}MAX-FileGuide is:@{uu}

   - not written in Hisoft Basic
   - only 25KB large
   - completely system compatible
   - Enforcer hits free
   - not A4000 Guru invoker
   - fast like a hell
   - completely configurable
   - fully localized

   Enough?

@endnode

@node Req "What it needs?"

   @{u}Requirements@{uu}

   To work MAX-FileGuide needs as follow:

   - any Amiga with at least OS2.1+
   - enough memory to hold whole database
   - turned on your power supply...
   - ...and MAX's BBS 1.53+ databases to process

@endnode


@node Features "What it can do?"

   @{u}Features@{uu}

   MAX-FileGuide  uses  locale.library  in its work. It allows you to see
 not  only  program's  messages  in your own language, but also generated
 file  list,  if you have got necessary catalog file for your language of
 course.  If there is no translation for your language and you want it to
 be,  then  look for "Blank.ct" file in the "CATALOGS" directory.
 It's  blank catalog translation file and the only thing you should do is
 to  fill the blank lines. Be careful and do not loose any trailing space
 nor  any  other  special character. Also make sure that your translation
 makes  sense!  Then  compile this file with "Blank.cd" and enjoy. And do
 not forget to send this ("#?.ct") file to me!

@endnode


@node Usage "How to use it?"

   @{u}Usage@{uu}

   MAX-FileGuide  can  be launched from CLI/Shell only (it will not crash
 when  called from Workbench however it will be not possible to pass any
 argument  to the program. It simply runs with default settings in mind).
 Before  you attempt to work, please read which arguments can be used and
 what for. Arguments may be abbreviated as shown in the brackets:

  FILE_DATA       (FD) - Your "file.data" file. Example:

                             FILE_DATA = HD2:BBS/Temp/file.data

                         If not specified "BBS:Files/file.data" will
                         be used by default.

  MAX_CONFIG      (MC) - Your "maxbbs.config" file. For example

                             MC = BBS:Config/maxbbs.config

                         If not specified "BBS:maxbbs.config" will
                         be used by default.

  OUTPUTFILE     (OUT) - AGuide file you want to create. E.g.

                             OUT = RAM:FileList.guide

                         If not specified "FileList.guide" will
                         be used by default.

  MESSAGETITLE    (MT) - Your name for Messages' button and section.
                         This feature needs any message file to be
                         specified. Example (quotes needs to be used
                         because of spaces in the name):

                             MT = "Important notes"

                         If not specified "Messages" will be used
                         by default.

  MESSAGEFILES   (MSG) - Name of your message files to be included in the
                         Message section. You may specify as many messages
                         as you want. Example:

                         MSG=HD2:Rules BBS:abc.txt DF0:BelovedPoems.txt                        

  BBSNAME        (BBS) - Name of your board. It will be placed in the
                         main menu header and inside filelist in version
                         string. Example:

                             BBS = "Silver Dream!'s BBS"

                         If not specified "BBS" will be used by default.

  BBSINFOFILE   (INFO) - ASCII file you want to be show when the user
                         clicks the BBSNAME button on the main page. It
                         should be info page about your BBS (like well-known
                         #?.displayme files, but you may place your poems
                         here as well :). If you do not specify the
                         file, BBSNAME will not become the button. Example:

                           BBSINFOFILE = hd1:Utils/Smieci01/SD!.displayme

  INFOTEXT       (TXT) - You have possibility to add one info line on the main
                         page (e.g. "Amiga Files only", "Windows sucks!").
                         
  GUIDEWIDTH      (GW) - Width (in characters) of visible page. This value
                         is used to center the main menu buttons in the
                         window. The width should be between 1 and 255.
                         The optimal, default, value is 74. Do not change
                         if you really have to.

  WORDWRAP        (WW) - Turns on the AmigaGuide's wordwrap feature on.
                         Default is off.

  BOLDOFF         (BO) - Turns off the boldfaces, which are ON by default.

  LANGUAGE      (LANG) - You can force MAX-FileGuide to use any language
                         by using this keyword. By default, program tries
                         to use language globally set for your system.
                         If it doesn't find necessary catalog file built-in
                         english strings will be used. E.g. to generate
                         polish (polski) filelist in your english system
                         use following formula in the command line:

                            LANGUAGE = polski

                         Of course you need proper catalog files for this.
                         If you can't find your language between them,
                         please take the blank.cd file from the archive
                         and do your best to translate it to your own
                         language. After all, please, send it to me
                         to let other users enjoy your work!

  NOEQUALWIDTH  (NOEQ) - By default, MAX-FileGuide calculates longest
                         text used for buttons on the page. This value
                         is then used to make nice-looking, same width
                         buttons on the page. If you do not like this,
                         simply disable it with this switch.

  NOSORT          (NS) - Do not sort the files. Speeds up the program
                         about milions times :), but makes whole list
                         more "useful" (in Microsoft's meaning :)
                         Sort is defaulty ON and do not touch it if
                         you like your users!

  NOSECTIONSORT  (NSS) - If you want sections to be shown by its number,
                         not alphabeticaly as by default, use this switch.
                         Do not touch until you really have to!

  PATTERN        (PAT) - You may force some sections to be excluded
                         (or included) using name pattern. Pattern
                         will be processed using system DOS functions,
                         so all pattern rules (#?, ~. [a-b]...) may
                         be used - for more information about pattern
                         power refere AmigaDOS manual. Exaples:
                         you want Amiga sections to be listed only, use
                         following pattern (those sections have to have
                         word "Amiga" in the name).

                              PATTERN = #?Amiga#?

  LASTDAYS        (LD) - You may need to filter older files out, for e.g. 
                         every-week (day, month, whatever) list of new
                         uploads. If so, use this to determine daylimit
                         (related to curent date): Example: to list
                         only files uploaded last week type:
                         
                             LASTDAYs = 7

  DOWNLOADS       (DL) - Normally MAX-FileGuide doesn't put download
                         counter for each file into result database, but
                         if you find useful to inform your users about
                         this, just switch this on.

  NOLINKx         (Lx) - MAX's BBS gives you possibility to 'attach' file to
                         one of three link (e.g. all Amiga sections are
                         attached to 1st link, all Mac sections to 2nd,
                         and all ZX Spectrum to 3rd). MAX-FileGuide gives
                         you (again :) possibility to simply ignore some
                         sections. By default it doesn't care about links,
                         but you may specify which are should be skipped. Use:
                         
                             NOLINK1 NOLINK2

                         to list only ZX Spectrum related sections.

  QUIET              (Q) - forces MAX-FileGuide to keep mouth shut

  NOTE: Default texts shown above are valid only for english, build-in
  version. Using other languages you should rather suppose polish/deutsh/
  spain or whatever strings instead of english one.

@endnode

@node Bugs "Are there any bugs left for me?"

  @{u}Bugs? Are you kidding?@{uu}

  There  is  no  bugs  at all neither in this program nor in any other of
 mine  because  I  always use professional Microsoft Turbo Pascal 7.0 for
 Microsoft  Windows  Chicago for Networks, Printers and for Workgroups to
 avoid  bugs!  Remeber  -  only  using  100%  bug-free tools for software
 creations lets you create bugless programs. Please support Microsoft.

 BTW: If you find any bug in this program, report it directly to Microsoft
      If you do not find anything report it either.

@endnode

